Definition 2.22. ($\operatorname{Mod}_{\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A})$) The category $\operatorname{Mod}_{\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A})$ is a dg-category made up of unital right dg-modules over $\mathcal{A}$ whose morphism complexes are $\operatorname{Mod}_{\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A})(N,N^{\prime})=\operatorname{Hom}_{% \mathcal{A}}(N,N^{\prime})$ of $\mathcal{A}$-linear maps with the differential $[d,\varphi]=d^{\prime}\circ\varphi-(-1)^{\varphi}\ \varphi\circ d.$ Setting $\phi_{1}=-\omega\circ\varphi\circ\sigma$ defines a “linear” morphism $\phi_{\bullet}=\phi_{1}\colon N[1]\to N^{\prime}[1]\in\operatorname{Mod_{% \infty}}(A)(N[1])(N^{\prime}[1])$ for which $\delta\phi_{\bullet}=-\omega\circ[d,\varphi]\circ\sigma$ and thus $\operatorname{Mod}_{\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A})$ includes as a subcategory of $\operatorname{Mod}_{\infty}(\mathcal{A}).$
Definition 2.3. (tensors) As usual, we have the graded $S$-module $M\otimes N$ for any graded $S$-modules $M$ and $N$. Morphisms and can be tensored: for $\phi\colon M\to N$ and $\psi\colon M^{\prime}\to N^{\prime},$ we have $\phi\otimes\psi\colon M\otimes M^{\prime}\to N\otimes N^{\prime}.$ This map is taken with Koszul signs; that is to say, for a tensor of homogeneous morphisms evaluated on a tensor of homogeneous elements, we have $(\phi\otimes\psi)(m\otimes m^{\prime})=(-1)^{|\psi||m|}\phi(m)\otimes\psi(m^{% \prime}).$
Definition 5.1. Suppose $k\in\mathbb{N}$ and $B\in{\mathbf{Rep}(S_{k})}$. A number $t\in\mathbb{C}$ is called $(k,B)$-exotic if there is a simple algebra $A$ in ${\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t})}$ such that • $A$ has level less than or equal to $k$, • there is an injection of objects $A\hookrightarrow{}^{\uparrow}B(t)$, and • $A$ is not isomorphic as an algebra to ${}^{\uparrow}C(t)$, for any $k^{\prime}$ and simple algebra $C\in{\mathbf{Rep}(S_{k^{\prime}})}$. If $t$ is not $(k,B)$-exotic, it is called $(k,B)$-ordinary.
Definition 3.2. Let $\operatorname{Alg}{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{*})}^{(k)}$ denote the pullback of $\operatorname{Alg}{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{*})}\rightarrow{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{*})}% \leftarrow{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{*})}^{(k)},$ where the first map is the evident underlying-object functor $\operatorname{Alg}\mathfrak{C}\to\mathfrak{C}$ and the second map is the inclusion.
Definition 2.8. The level of an indecomposable object $L(\lambda)$ is defined to be the size $|\lambda|$ of $\lambda$. The level of any object is defined to be the maximum level of any indecomposable summand of that object.
Definition 2.3. Given a map $\varphi:R\to R^{\prime}$, there is a family of monoidal functors $\varphi_{*}:{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t},R)}\to{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{\varphi(t)},R^{\prime})}$ indexed by $t\in R$. (We suppress $t$ in the notation.) Specifically, we define $\varphi_{*0}:{\mathrm{Rep}_{0}(S_{t},R)}\to{\mathrm{Rep}_{0}(S_{\varphi(t)},R^% {\prime})}$ to be the identity on objects and send a morphism $f=\sum_{\pi\in P_{a+b}}f_{\pi}\pi:a\to b$ to $\sum_{\pi\in P_{a+b}}\varphi(f_{\pi})\pi:a\to b$. The functor $\varphi_{*}$ is then defined to be the extension of $\varphi_{*0}$ to ${\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t},R)}$ which comes from the universal properties of completion under direct sums and idempotents.
Definition 2.1 ([CO11]). For $R$ a commutative ring and $t\in R$, the $R$-linear monoidal category ${\mathrm{Rep}_{0}(S_{t},R)}$ is defined to have finite sets as objects and $\mathrm{Hom}(a,b)=R[P_{a+b}]$. • The identity element of $\mathrm{Hom}(a,a)$ is the partition whose parts are $\{\iota_{0}x,\iota_{1}x\}$ for all $x\in a$. • Composition is the $R$-bilinear extension of a function $-\circ-:P_{b+c}\times P_{a+b}\to R[P_{a+c}],$ defined as follows. Given $\rho\in P_{b+c}$ and $\pi\in P_{a+b}$, let $\rho\vee\pi$ be the finest partition on $a+b+c$ containing $\rho$ and $\pi$. Letting $\rho\cdot\pi$ denote the restriction of $\rho\vee\pi$ to $a+c$, and letting $d(\rho,\pi)$ denote the number of parts of $\rho\vee\pi$ containing only elements of $b$, we define $\rho\circ\pi$ to be $t^{d(\rho,\pi)}\rho\cdot\pi$. • The tensor product of two objects is their disjoint union, with unit $[0]$. On morphisms, the tensor product is the $R$-bilinear extension of a function $-\otimes-:P_{a+b}\times P_{a^{\prime}+b^{\prime}}\to P_{a+a^{\prime}+b+b^{% \prime}}.$ The partition $\pi\otimes\pi^{\prime}$ of $a+a^{\prime}+b+b^{\prime}$ partitions $a+b$ as $\pi$ does and $a^{\prime}+b^{\prime}$ as $\pi^{\prime}$ does, and is finest among such.
Definition 3.3. If $A$ is an object in ${\mathbf{Rep}(S_{k})}$, we define ${}^{\uparrow}A$ to be the section $\operatorname{Ind}_{S_{k}\times S_{*-k}}^{S_{*}}(A\boxtimes\mathbb{C})$ of ${\mathrm{Rep}(S_{*})}^{(k)}$. If $A$ is an algebra in ${\mathbf{Rep}(S_{k})}$, we define ${}^{\uparrow}A$ to be $\operatorname{Ind}_{S_{k}\times S_{*-k}}^{S_{*}}(A\boxtimes\mathbb{C})$, together with the induced algebra structure, considered as an section of $\operatorname{Alg}{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{*})}^{(k)}$. We also write $U_{A}$ for the (Zariski-open, cofinite) subset of $\mathbb{A}_{\mathbb{C}}^{1}$ on which ${}^{\uparrow}A$ is defined.
Definition 2.2 ([CO11]). The category ${\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t},R)}$ is defined to be the category obtained by starting with ${\mathrm{Rep}_{0}(S_{t},R)}$, then adjoining direct sums, then taking the idempotent completion (also called the Karoubification). We write ${\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t})}$ for ${\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t},\mathbb{C})}$, etc.
Definition 2.6 ([Eti14]). The restriction functor $\operatorname{Res}_{S_{k}\times S_{t-k}}^{S_{t}}:{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t})}\to{% \mathbf{Rep}(S_{k})}\boxtimes{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t-k})}$ is defined to be the monoidal functor that sends $\mathfrak{h}\in{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t})}$ to the Frobenius algebra $\mathfrak{h}\boxtimes\mathbb{C}\oplus\mathbb{C}\boxtimes\mathfrak{h}$. The induction functor $\operatorname{Ind}_{S_{k}\times S_{t-k}}^{S_{t}}:{\mathbf{Rep}(S_{k})}% \boxtimes{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t-k})}\to{\mathrm{Rep}(S_{t})}$ is defined to be the left adjoint to restriction.
Definition 2.4. For two $R$-linear categories $\mathcal{A}$, $\mathcal{B}$ the external tensor product $\mathcal{A}\boxtimes\mathcal{B}$ is generated under direct sums by objects $A\boxtimes B$ for $A\in\mathcal{A}$, $B\in\mathcal{B}$, with $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}\boxtimes\mathcal{B}}(A\boxtimes B,A^{\prime}% \boxtimes B^{\prime})=\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(A,A^{\prime})\otimes_{R}% \mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}(B,B^{\prime})$. If $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ are monoidal categories, $\mathcal{A}\boxtimes\mathcal{B}$ inherits a monoidal structure with $(A\boxtimes B)\otimes(A^{\prime}\boxtimes B^{\prime})=(A\otimes A^{\prime})% \boxtimes(B\otimes B^{\prime})$, etc.
Definition 3.1. Following the notation of [Mat13], for all schemes $S$, there is a functor $\operatorname{Alg}$ from the category $\mathbf{MonAbCat}_{S}$ of monoidal Ab-enriched categories over $S$ to the category $\mathbf{Cat}_{S}$ of categories over $S$ that sends $\mathfrak{C}$ to the category of algebras internal to $\mathfrak{C}$.
Definition 1. Let $n$ be a positive integer. An $n$-composition-series of the derived category $\mathcal{D}A$ of an algebra $A$ is a chain of derived categories of algebras linked by fully faithful triangle functors $0=\mathcal{D}B_{l}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i_{l}}}{{\hookrightarrow}}\mathcal{D% }B_{l-1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i_{l-1}}}{{\hookrightarrow}}\cdots\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle i_{2}}}{{\hookrightarrow}}\mathcal{D}B_{1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i% _{1}}}{{\hookrightarrow}}\mathcal{D}B_{0}=\mathcal{D}A$ such that, for all $p=1,2,\cdots,l$, the triangle functor $\mathcal{D}B_{p}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i_{p}}}{{\hookrightarrow}}\mathcal{D}B% _{p-1}$ can be completed to an $n$-recollement $\xymatrix@!=4pc{\mathcal{D}B_{p}\ar[r]^{-}{i_{p}}&\mathcal{D}B_{p-1}\ar@<-3ex>% [l]\ar@<+3ex>[l]^{-}{\vdots}\ar[r]&\mathcal{D}C_{p}\ar@<-3ex>[l]\ar@<+3ex>[l]^% {-}{\vdots}}$ for some $n$-derived-simple algebra $C_{p}$. In this case, $\mathcal{D}C_{1},\mathcal{D}C_{2},\cdots,\mathcal{D}C_{l}$ are called the $n$-composition-factors of $\mathcal{D}A$. Moreover, $\mathcal{D}C_{p}$ is said to be of multiplicity $m_{p}$ if it appears exactly $m_{p}$ times in the sequence $\mathcal{D}C_{1},\mathcal{D}C_{2},\cdots,\mathcal{D}C_{l}$ up to derived equivalence.
Definition 7. System ${\rm A}\otimes{\rm B}$ allows for local tomography iff, for every pair of states $\rho,\rho^{\prime}\in\mathsf{St}({\rm A}\otimes{\rm B})$, one has the implication $\displaystyle\begin{aligned} \displaystyle\xymatrix@*=<0em>@C=1em@R=.7em@!R{*+% <1em,.9em>{\hphantom{\rho}}\save[0,0].[1,0];p\save!C*{\rho},p+RU+<0em,0em>;+LU% +<+.8em,0em>**\dir{-}\restore\save+RD;+RU**\dir{-}\restore\save+RD;+LD+<.8em,0% em>**\dir{-}\restore\save+LD+<0em,.8em>;+LU-<0em,.8em>**\dir{-}\restore\POS!UL% *!UL{\cir<.9em>{u_{r}}};!DL*!DL{\cir<.9em>{l_{u}}}\restore&\displaystyle{{}^{{% \rm A}}}\ar@{-}[0,-1]&\displaystyle*{\xy*+=+<.5em>{\vphantom{\rule{0.0pt}{1.0% pt}a}}*\cir{r_{l}};p\save*!R{a}\restore\save+UC;+UC-<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{a}% }+L**\dir{-}\restore\save+DC;+DC-<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{a}}+L**\dir{-}% \restore\POS+UC-<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{a}}+L;+DC-<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{a}}+% L**\dir{-}\endxy}\ar@{-}[0,-1]\\ \displaystyle*+<1em,.9em>&\displaystyle{{}^{{\rm B}}}\ar@{-}[0,-1]&% \displaystyle*{\xy*+=+<.5em>{\vphantom{\rule{0.0pt}{1.0pt}b}}*\cir{r_{l}};p% \save*!R{b}\restore\save+UC;+UC-<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{b}}+L**\dir{-}\restore% \save+DC;+DC-<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{b}}+L**\dir{-}\restore\POS+UC-<.5em,0em>*% !R{\hphantom{b}}+L;+DC-<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{b}}+L**\dir{-}\endxy}\ar@{-}[0,% -1]\end{aligned}=\begin{aligned} \displaystyle\xymatrix@*=<0em>@C=1em@R=.7em@!% R{*+<1em,.9em>{\hphantom{\rho^{\prime}}}\save[0,0].[1,0];p\save!C*{\rho^{% \prime}},p+RU+<0em,0em>;+LU+<+.8em,0em>**\dir{-}\restore\save+RD;+RU**\dir{-}% \restore\save+RD;+LD+<.8em,0em>**\dir{-}\restore\save+LD+<0em,.8em>;+LU-<0em,.% 8em>**\dir{-}\restore\POS!UL*!UL{\cir<.9em>{u_{r}}};!DL*!DL{\cir<.9em>{l_{u}}}% \restore&\displaystyle{{}^{{\rm A}}}\ar@{-}[0,-1]&\displaystyle*{\xy*+=+<.5em>% {\vphantom{\rule{0.0pt}{1.0pt}a}}*\cir{r_{l}};p\save*!R{a}\restore\save+UC;+UC% -<.5em,0em>*!R{\hphantom{a}}+L**\dir{-}\restore\save+DC;+DC-<.5em,0em>*!R{% \hphantom{a}}+L**\dir{-}\restore\POS+UC-<.5em,0em>*!